In Rust, the output encoding is determined by the environment in which your program is running. By default, Rust uses the UTF-8 encoding.

However, if you need to specify a different encoding for your program's output, you can use the `stdout` field of the `Command` struct and set the encoding explicitly. Here's an example:

```rust
use std::process::Command;
use std::io::{self, Write};
use std::env::consts::OS;

fn main() -> io::Result<()> {
    let mut command = Command::new("echo");
    command.arg("Hello, World!");

    if OS == "windows" {
        command.stdout(std::process::Stdio::piped());

        let child = command.spawn()?;
        let stdout = child.stdout.ok_or_else(|| io::Error::new(io::ErrorKind::Other, "Failed to capture stdout"))?;

        let stdout_handle = io::BufReader::new(stdout);
        for line in stdout_handle.lines() {
            match line {
                Ok(line) => {
                    let coded_line: Vec<u16> = line.encode_utf16().collect();
                    let output_line = String::from_utf16_lossy(&coded_line[..]);
                    println!("{}", output_line);
                },
                Err(error) => eprintln!("Failed to read stdout line: {}", error),
            }
        }
    } else {
        let output = command.output()?;
        let result = String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout);
        println!("{}", result);
    }

    Ok(())
}
```

This code snippet is platform-specific to handle the Windows command prompt, which uses the UTF-16 encoding. On Windows, it redirects the `stdout` of the child process, reads the output as UTF-16, and converts it into a Rust string using `String::from_utf16_lossy()`.

For other platforms, it simply captures the standard output using `command.output()` and assumes UTF-8 encoding.

Please remember to adjust the code according to your specific use case and target platform.

